          - You see recovery as weakness or laziness<br/><br/>
          <strong>The assessment:</strong> Be honest with yourself. Which list describes you more?<br/><br/>
          <strong>The good news:</strong> Ambition style is not fixed. You can shift from toxic to regulated with awareness, practice, and support.
        </p>
      )
    },
    {
      id: 'high-intensity',
      title: 'What if I am in a high-intensity season (product launch, conference) and need to push harder than usual? Is that toxic ambition?',
      content: (
        <p>
          <strong>Not necessarily—IF it is time-limited and intentional.</strong><br/><br/>
          <strong>High-intensity seasons are part of regulated ambition when:</strong><br/>
          - <strong>They are planned:</strong> You know it is coming and prepare<br/>
          - <strong>They are time-limited:</strong> 3-6 months maximum, not indefinite<br/>
          - <strong>They are followed by recovery:</strong> You build in downtime after<br/>
          - <strong>They are sustainable:</strong> You are not already depleted before you start<br/><br/>
          <strong>Toxic ambition is:</strong><br/>
          - <strong>Perpetual:</strong> Always in high-intensity mode, no recovery<br/>
          - <strong>Unplanned:</strong> Constantly reacting to crises, never designing your seasons<br/>
          - <strong>Unsupported:</strong> No recovery, no boundaries, no systems<br/><br/>
          <strong>The key:</strong> Design your high-intensity seasons intentionally. They are part of a broader pattern of sustainable ambition—not the whole pattern.
        </p>
      )
    },
    {
      id: 'after-burnout',
      title: 'I have already burned out. Is it too late to build regulated ambition?',
      content: (
        <p>
          <strong>Absolutely not.</strong> Burnout is the wake-up call, not the end.<br/><br/>
          <strong>Regulated ambition after burnout:</strong><br/>
          - <strong>Rebuild first:</strong> Focus on recovery before achievement (health, relationships, meaning)<br/>
          - <strong>Start smaller:</strong> You may not be able to handle as much as before—and that is okay<br/>
          - <strong>Learn from it:</strong> Burnout taught you what does not work. Honor that wisdom<br/>
          - <strong>Build differently:</strong> This time, build a career that works WITH your human needs, not against them<br/><br/>
          <strong>The paradox:</strong> Many high achievers report that post-burnout, they are MORE successful. Why? Because they are finally working sustainably, not destructively.<br/><br/>
          <strong>You are not starting over.</strong> You are starting over with wisdom. That is an advantage.
        </p>
      )
    }
  ]}
/>

## Conclusion

<Callout type="success" title="The Sustainable Ambition Promise">
**Your best work is sustainable work.**

Toxic ambition promises glory through self-destruction. It delivers short-term achievement and long-term breakdown.

**Regulated ambition promises achievement WITH well-being.** It delivers sustained excellence over decades, not quarters.

**The regulated ambition practices**—honoring capacity, designing for decades, prioritizing recovery, redefining success holistically—allow you to achieve at a high level without sacrificing your health, relationships, or meaning.

**The quarterly ambition check** prevents drift into toxic patterns. Every 90 days, ask: *"Is this sustainable?"* Adjust if it is not.

**Redefining success** beyond output creates a life you love, not just a career you are addicted to.

**Modeling regulated ambition** creates healthy culture where your team achieves sustainably, following your lead.

**Ambition that burns you out is not ambition—it is self-destruction.**

**Sustainable ambition is the art of pursuing high achievement for decades, not quarters.**

**Your best work? It is the work that does not destroy you.**

**Start building regulated ambition today.** Your future self will thank you.
</Callout>

